2026-04-25 | Reduce Array by Opposite Sign Collisions

Question
Return final array after all operations.
	Key Insight
This behaves like a **collision problem (similar to asteroid collision)**.  
So we use a stack to simulate left-to-right processing.
	Approach
1.	Initialize empty stack  
2.	Traverse array:
		for each element x:
			while stack not empty AND top and x have opposite signs:
				resolve collision  
3.	Collision logic:
		if abs(top) < abs(x):
			pop top and continue  
		if abs(top) > abs(x):
			discard x  
		if equal:
			pop top and discard x  
4.	If x survives → push to stack  
5.	Return stack as result  
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> finalArray(vector<int>& arr) {
        vector<int> st;
        for(int x : arr){
            bool alive = true;
            while(!st.empty() && alive &&
                  ((st.back() > 0 && x < 0) || (st.back() < 0 && x > 0))){
                if(abs(st.back()) < abs(x)){
                    st.pop_back();
                }
                else if(abs(st.back()) > abs(x)){
                    alive = false;
                }
                else{
                    st.pop_back();
                    alive = false;
                }
            }
            if(alive){
                st.push_back(x);
            }
        }
        return st;
    }
};
	Key Insight
We simulate interactions using a stack:
		only adjacent opposite signs interact  
This ensures:
		each element is processed once → O(n)  
This is a classic **collision reduction problem**.
